Composing systems from component parts provides massive leverage and affects most aspects of computer science. *Effect Systems* produce composability that is both easy and scalable. 

The main benefit of easy composability is that people do not resist using it. This results in better designs because components are created based on fitness to purpose rather than an arbitrary constraint such as size.

Composability must withstand the problems of scale. A solution might work well in the small, but become impractical as system size and complexity increase. You can find numerous solutions that were introduced to solve scaling issues:

**Namespaces**. Some early high-level languages expected the entire program to be contained in a single file. Even when multi-file languages appeared, the programmer was responsible for preventing name collisions (often this could happen quietly, producing hidden bugs). This produced scaling issues, especially when using third-party libraries. Requiring names to live within a namespace makes them uniquely identifiable, eliminating the scaling problem. (Specific case of the general idea of scopes).

**Version control**. Namespaces prevent collisions by creating unique names. A version control system makes program elements unique over *time*. If you can’t go back to an earlier version of a program element, it makes experimentation much harder, which produces a scaling limitation.

**Test automation**. The best time to check the validity of your code is during compilation, and for this we rely heavily on the type system. There are limits to what you can check at compile time; for everything else you must provide tests. When testing is part of the automated build process, you see failures immediately after a change, so you know it’s *that* change that caused it.

**Language features**. Dynamic binding, for example, doesn’t scale because every method call assumes you must discover object information from scratch. This produces unacceptable overhead for many applications. Although clever runtime optimizations can help for special cases, some languages eventually added pattern matching. This determines characteristics the compiler can use to make more efficient calls. As a second example, the “infinite operator overloading” experiment in Scala did not scale because it produced incomprehensible strings of symbols that humans could not decode or memorize.

**Program Dependencies**. Are all necessary resources available and initialized? Inversion of control helps, but requires bookkeeping. As systems get larger, it becomes harder to discover dependency cycles.

**Object-Oriented Programming.** This has been our biggest swing at the problem of scalable composition. Objects are composed from other objects. Even inheritance is composition, with extra steps. The valuable core of object-oriented programming is the user-defined data type. Unfortunately, the benefit of attaching every possible operation to each class didn't scale as well as we hoped. Inheritance hierarchies definitely don't scale. In the end, we don’t want to compose *objects*, but rather *operations*. A program's essence is not that it *is* something, but rather that it *does* something. 

# When Effect Systems Make Sense

If you’ve never worked with a large, complex system, the concepts in this book might not seem relevant to you. Although we’ve tried to boil our examples down to their essence, it is not possible to make a case for an Effect System using trivial “hello world”-style examples.

This book argues that an Effect System is required to scalably compose operations.

Because an Effect System solves multiple problems, it is easy to become fixated on one aspect before you understand the big picture. In many cases, introductions use error handling as a first example. While this is a compelling hook, it’s easy to stop at error handling and miss out on all the other benefits. Also, this approach to error handling can be implemented apart from an Effect System, and you see it used this way in languages such as Rust and Go. 

# Composable Operations

You’ll notice we’ve been using the generic term “operation” and this may sound like it means “function.” That is correct: functions compose by calling other functions. We can compose a new function consisting of calls to an **add()** function. In this chapter, we’ll use a generic pseudocode:

**`def add(x: a, y: a): a with Add[a] = x + y  // Hide`**

**`def f(a: Int32, b: Int32): Int32 =`**  
  **`let x = add(a, 10);`**  
  **`let y = add(b, 100);`**  
  **`add(x, y) // Returns this result`**

**`def main(): Unit \ IO =  // Hide`**  
    **`println(f(11, 42))`**  
     
Here, composition works seamlessly. For given values of **a** and **b**, you will always get the same result – this is so reliable that we can replace the function with a table lookup. Nothing ever fails, so **f()** never blows up with an exception.

Function composition doesn’t always work this way. Indeed, **add()** and **f()** are special cases, examples of what we call a *pure function*. Pure functions compose seamlessly, but many functions are not pure. Consider a variation of **f()**:

**`mod Time {  // Hide`**  
    **`pub def ofDay(): Int64 \ Clock =`**  
        **`Clock.currentTime(TimeUnit.Milliseconds)`**  
**`}`**

**`mod Rand {  // Hide`**  
    **`pub def number(): Int64 \ Random =`**  
        **`Random.randomInt64()`**  
**`}`** 

**`def add(x: a, y: a): a with Add[a] = x + y   // Hide`**  
**`def divide(x: a, y: a): a with Div[a] = x / y  // Hide`**

**`// Hide signature:`**  
**`def g(a: Int64, b: Int64): Int64 \ {Clock, Random} =`**  
  **`let x = add(a, Time.ofDay());`**  
  **`let y = divide(b, Rand.number());`**  
  **`add(x, y)`**

**`def main(): Unit \ {IO, NonDet} =   // Hide`**  
    **`run {`**  
        **`println(g(11i64, 42i64))`**  
    **`} with Clock.runWithIO with Random.runWithIO`**

Now the result for **x** is different every time you call **timeOfDay()**. Because **y** is calculated using **Random.number()**, it is also different for each call. Providing **g()** with identical values of **a** and **b** produces a different result for each call. While the result of **f()** is predictable and consistent, the result of **g()** is not.

We’ve also calculated **y** using **divide()**. This introduces two more issues: first, it is possible for **random\_number()** to produce zero, which causes a divide-by-zero error. This is expressed in many languages as an exception, which destroys the computation and routes execution into an alternate exception-handling mechanism. We traditionally define functions to expect inputs and to produce a single consistent result – they assume purity. The exception-handling experiment is admittedly better than ignoring errors but in the end exceptions have their own issues that make them non-composable.

A more subtle issue is testing: fault conditions often happen rarely and are difficult to reproduce (for example, **Random.number()** can be called many times without producing zero, and **Clock.timeOfDay()** can be called many times without producing midnight). As a result, failure systems might not get tested, in which case you only discover faulty failure-handling code in production. For reliable testing we must be able to easily reproduce fault conditions.

These are just some of the issues that make impure functions difficult to compose. Basically, anytime a function touches the outside world the result becomes unpredictable. If you ask for information from an external system (such as a server) you don’t know whether that system will respond, how long it takes to respond, and what the result might be. The predictability of the result of that function impacts any function that calls it, especially when testing. Those issues bleed outward, making your function non-composable as well.

Historically, a big part of programming has dealt with all these things we’ve been calling “wiring,” and are formally referred to as *side effects*. If you step back and look at the larger picture, you’ll see that all this wiring is repetitive busy work. Vast amounts of time and money are spent on wiring, and even more when you want to refactor something – this makes us resist refactoring and thus slows or prevents improvements to systems.

# Automatically Wiring Operations

The main barrier to composing operations is wiring those operations together. This, and testing, is where the programming team spends its time. This is the hurdle to both rapid development and refactoring. Taking care of all that wiring adds cost and tedium, increasing the work of construction and dramatically reducing the appeal of refactoring.

We need a system that automatically takes care of the wiring when we compose operations. That is what an Effect System does. By automatically wiring your operations together, an effect system removes the tedium and overhead from the programmer. Additions and changes that might typically take weeks can be achieved in a matter of minutes.

Most of the work you do when composing a system involves these repetitive wiring activities: 

Resource management: initialization, cleanup, and dependencies  
Error handling   
I/O: Communication with remote devices or systems

# Exposing the Wires

To achieve automated assembly during composition, we must somehow expose the “wires” (side effects) of impure functions. When the Effect System sees the wires, it can fit components together correctly, like a plug going into an electrical socket.

There are several ways to expose the wires. The approach used here packages all necessary information into the return type of an operation. This tells the Effect System how to properly connect one operation to another. When you call a function that takes a parameter that is of one of these operations, the compiler checks that the return type of the argument lines up with what the parameter expects.

These return types are complicated to look at, so in this book we rely on implicit return types – we don’t write them out explicitly. As a user, you don’t need to know how the wires are exposed. Many people have been turned away from Effect Systems because they see the insides too soon.

## What it Looks Like

If we imagine each operation (function) is a block, and the various issues we must  program around (results, errors, quirks) are wires, the process of assembling components could look like this:  
![][image1]  
The **Result** is the actual value an operation produces; traditionally this is the only thing returned from the function. This diagram shows everything else that happens when you call that function. Historically, the programmer must write code to compensate for all these hanging “wires.”

We assume each type of error throws a different kind of exception and must be handled differently, or caught at a higher level, or ignored and caught at the top level which will terminate the program. Most exception-handling systems don’t track or guarantee that all errors will be handled.

The “Quirks” are the rest of the things that affect the program when the operation is called. When an operation writes to a database, for example, it causes a state change in the outside world. The world is different after performing that operation. If an operation gets data from the user or a server or gets the time of day or uses a random number generator, this influences the output of that operation, which can have various impacts during composition but in particular influences testing – those factors require controlled results in order to properly reproduce test conditions.

Every one of these “wires,” even the **Result**, can be considered a *side effect*: something irreversible that occurs as a consequence of performing the operation. Without an Effect System, the programmer is responsible for writing code that manages all the side effects, which is often repetitive, tedious, and error-prone. Because the side effects are not tracked in any way, the programmer must also know about them, either relying on the accuracy of the documentation or looking through the source code for side-effecting behavior. This practice does not scale.

To compose operations without requiring the programmer to manage all these side effects, we need to somehow capture each set of wires into a connector, so the act of programming becomes simply pushing connectors together.  
![][image2]

Now each operation encapsulates its own side effects, turning that operation into an *Effect*. This is unfortunate terminology because now “Effect” uses the same word contained in the phrase “Side Effect.” They are two different but conflated ideas: Side Effects are all the quirks, while an Effect encapsulates those quirks. Conceptually, an Effect is an operation along with a connector. The connector provides a standardized way to compose that operation with other Effects.

Note that the “Effect Connector” is not universal. That is, each “Effect Connector” can contain a different combination of types for the Result, Errors, and Quirks. If a programmer tries to connect Effects that don’t have compatible connectors, the compiler will report this as a type error, preventing you from mis-wiring your Effects. You must resolve the mismatch (possibly by inserting another effect). When your program compiles it means the Effect System has successfully “wired” your Effects together during composition.

## What We Want From An Effect System

To summarize, here are are all the features in an Effect System that produce composability at scale:

* Guarantee that all errors are handled  
* Automate error handling to minimize coding  
* Control test results to ensure that failure cases are exercised  
* Easy parallel execution  
* (automatic?) async execution  
* Guarantee all necessary resources are available, created & cleaned up in the correct order  
* …

# Initialization & Cleanup

As initialization and cleanup are actions that must be performed for every system, we would also like to offload these to the Effect System. This ensures proper creation of the resources necessary to execute the program, and if necessary the resources are shut down at the end of the program.

Resources can require other resources, so we must somehow guarantee that all resources exist and are created in the right order, and also that we don’t accidentally create dependency loops during initialization. This is possible in the small but rapidly becomes unmanageable as system scale increases.

# Delayed Execution

Procrastination is commonly demonized, and people are admonished to *do it now*\! Overcoming procrastination is presented as the most basic way to solve productivity problems.

This is oversimplified. You can probably think of cases where procrastination proved to be a benefit. Some problems, given time, solved themselves. Some tasks, it turned out, didn’t need doing. Some projects depend on other projects, so time spent on them might need repeating when those other projects come to fruition.

Delayed execution is an essential part of an Effect System. The Effect System runtime makes decisions based on the results of other Effects, which it cannot know until those Effects are actually executed, at runtime. For example, suppose you make a request to a remote server. Only if that server takes too long to respond, or gives a bad answer, can the runtime apply a different strategy to get that result. It turns out that certain aspects of composition simply do not work without delayed execution, because the runtime must have the ability to decide *when* an Effect is performed.

Executing an Effect is irreversible

In most programming languages, function calls happen immediately:

**`let result = fetch(url)  // Network request happens NOW`**

Effect systems take a different approach. Calling an Effect doesn't call the function, but instead returns a *description* of what will happen—a data structure representing the Effect. The Effect only executes when you explicitly run that description through the Effect System runtime, which you can think of as a very lightweight interpreter.

**`let program = fetch(url)  // No network request yet—just a description`**  
**`let result = run(program) // NOW the request happens`**

This indirection might seem like unnecessary complexity. Why can't we achieve composability by simply providing a complete interface to effects? Why must execution be delayed?

The answer is deeper than performance optimization. Delayed execution enables composition operations that would otherwise be *impossible*.

## Composition Requires Execution Control

Consider these combinators:

`def retry(effect: Eff[a, e], times: Int32): Eff[a, e]`  
`def timeout(effect: Eff[a, e], duration: Duration): Eff[a, e + Timeout]`  
`def ifThenElse(cond: Bool, onTrue: Eff[a, e], onFalse: Eff[a, e]): Eff[a, e]`

Each requires control over *when* and *whether* execution happens. That control *is* the composition.

`retry` isn't "run this and retry the result." It's "run this, and if it fails, run it again." You cannot "run again" something that isn't a description. Once an effect executes, no interface can retroactively re-execute it.

Similarly, `timeout` must be able to cancel execution. If the effect already ran, there's nothing to cancel.

`bracket(acquire, use, release)` guarantees that `release` runs after `use`, even on failure. If `acquire` executes immediately upon being called, you've lost control of the sequencing that makes the guarantee possible.

This reveals the core principle: certain composition operations *are* execution control. You cannot compose execution control over things that have already executed.

## Seeing the Whole Before Committing to Parts

A second consideration emerges when we look at independent operations:

`// Immediate execution - decisions locked in at each call`  
`let result1 = fetch(url1)  // runs NOW, commits to sequential`  
`let result2 = fetch(url2)  // runs NOW, can't parallelize`

`// Delayed execution - combine first, decide later`  
`let program = Eff.zip(fetch(url1), fetch(url2))  // description only`  
`// runtime sees BOTH, can choose to parallelize`

Even with a perfect API, you cannot un-execute something. Once `fetch(url1)` runs, no interface can retroactively parallelize it with a later fetch.

This enables separation of concerns: business logic declares *what* should happen, while the runtime decides *how*—choosing retry strategies, parallelism, and resource management.

## Dynamic Execution Trees

Is the execution tree fixed at compile time? No—the tree unfolds dynamically based on runtime values.

**`def transfer(fromAcct: Account, toAcct: Account, amount: Int32): Eff[Unit, DbError] =`**  
    **`foreach (`**  
        **`bal <- getBalance(fromAcct)`**  
    **`) yield {`**  
        **`if (bal < amount)`**  
            **`Eff.fail("Insufficient funds")`**  
        **`else`**  
            **`foreach (`**  
                **`_ <- withdraw(fromAcct, amount);`**  
                **`_ <- deposit(toAcct, amount)`**  
            **`) yield ()`**  
    **`} |> Eff.flatten`**

Whether `deposit` even *exists* in the tree depends on what `getBalance` returns. The tree's shape depends on runtime values.

This is the essential distinction between `map` and `flatMap`:

- **map** transforms values; tree shape unchanged  
- **flatMap** computes the next effect from the previous result; tree grows dynamically

The runtime cannot see the whole tree upfront—it discovers the tree by running. Each step reveals the next branch.

This creates a tension with "seeing the whole." More precisely: the runtime sees as much as is statically determined (enabling parallelization of independent branches), but must execute sequentially through `flatMap` boundaries where the next step depends on a result.

**`Eff.zip(fetch(a), fetch(b))             // Both visible, can parallelize`**  
**`Eff.flatMap(fetch(a), x -> fetch(x))    // Second unknown until first completes`**

The description is a *lazily unfolding* tree, not a fixed blueprint.

## Walkthrough: Delayed Execution in Practice

Let's trace through a concrete example to see how delayed execution works. Consider a function to fetch a user's profile, then fetch their recent orders:

**`def getUserSummary(userId: Int32): Eff[Summary, HttpError] =`**  
    **`foreach (`**  
        **`user   <- fetchUser(userId);`**  
        **`orders <- fetchOrders(user.id)`**  
    **`) yield Summary(user, orders)`**

**Step 1: Building the description**

If we call `getUserSummary(42)`, no network requests occur. Instead, we construct a data structure roughly equivalent to:

**`FlatMap(`**  
    **`effect: FetchUser(42),`**  
    **`continuation: user -> Map(`**  
        **`effect: FetchOrders(user.id),`**  
        **`transform: orders -> Summary(user, orders)`**  
    **`)`**  
**`)`**

At this point, we have a value we can inspect, transform, or combine with other descriptions.

**Step 2: Combining descriptions**

Perhaps we want to add a timeout:

**`let programWithTimeout = Eff.timeout(program, Duration.seconds(5))`**

This wraps our description in another layer—still no execution. The timeout combinator doesn't need to know the internals of our program; it just needs the description to control.

**Step 3: Interpretation begins**

Invoking the runtime on our function causes the following:

1. `FetchUser(42)` performs the network request  
2. The request returns `User(id = 42, name = "Alice")`  
3. It passes this value to the continuation function  
4. The continuation produces a *new* description: `FetchOrders(42)`  
5. The runtime performs this second request  
6. The result flows through `map` to produce the final `Summary`

Throughout this process, the timeout combinator monitors elapsed time and can cancel execution if the limit is exceeded.

**Key insight**

Notice that the second network request (`FetchOrders`) didn't exist in our original description—it was created dynamically when the continuation ran. The runtime discovered the full computation by executing it step by step, while still maintaining control over *how* each step executed.

This is the power of delayed execution: we describe computations as composable values, combine them freely, then hand control to a runtime that can manage execution with full knowledge of the structure—even as that structure unfolds dynamically.

# The Rules

Here are the basic concepts/rules for an Effect System:

1. An Effect is a function “with extra steps.”  
2. An Effect exposes all the side effects it produces.  
3. An Effect contains a thunk (an argument-less function definition) that calls the function with all its arguments bound. This produces *delayed execution*.  
4. Each Effect declares its required dependencies (services, resources, other Effects, non-Effect arguments) in its type signature.The type system guarantees at compile time that all dependencies are satisfied. At runtime, concrete implementations of those dependencies are provided when the Effect is finally executed.  
5. All dependencies that are themselves Effects are also thunks and so also have delayed execution; they are not run until they are needed (so sometimes we have to run them explicitly using **.run** ?)  
6. To run the program, hand the starting Effect to the Effect System Runtime. The Runtime:  
   1. Creates the necessary dependencies for that Effect  
   2. Calls the Effect’s function while providing those dependencies.   
   3. Effects used by that function are run as they are needed.

![][image3]  
**(Only here as a conversation starter)**

Pure functions trivially parallelize (no shared state). For effectful code, it depends on the system:

* ZIO: You explicitly choose with combinators like zipPar; the system doesn't auto-verify safety  
* Effect.ts: There’s only one thread, so parallelization issues magically vanish\!  
* Algebraic effect systems (Koka, Flix): Can potentially reason about effect independence since effects are tracked more granularly

Is every Effect automatically async?  
No. You get control over this. ZIO effects are descriptions—you choose sync vs async execution with operators like fork. The runtime may use fibers (lightweight threads), but async isn't automatic or implicit.

# Pseudocode

We said earlier that you can’t write a meaningful equivalent of “Hello, world” for an Effect System. Without the scaling problems in larger systems you only see the extra syntax and not the benefits. It is useful to see examples in pseudocode so you can get comfortable with the basic structure of Effect Oriented programs, before we get into language specifics in the remainder of the book.

The first example registers a new user:

// possible break apart type Database.save & Email.send

Database.save(user): Effect\<  
  requires=Database,  
  errors=DBError  
  returns=User  
\>

Email.send(sendArgs): Effect\<  
  requires=EmailServer,  
  errors=EmailError,  
  returns=Nothing  
\>

**`function registerUser(email, password):`**   
  **`Effect<`**  
    **`requires=Database & EmailServer,`**  
    **`errors=DBError | EmailError`**  
    **`result=User`**  
  **`> =  {`**  
  **`user = User(email, hashPassword(password))`**  
  **`savedUser = Database.save(user))`**  
    
  **`run(`**  
    **`Email.send(`**  
      **`to = savedUser.email,`**  
      **`subject = "Welcome!",`**  
      **`body = "Thanks for registering"`**  
    **`)`**  
  **`)`**  
    
  **`return savedUser`**  
**`}`**

**`# Requires: Database, Email`**  
**`# Errors: DBError | EmailError | ValidationError`**    
**`# Returns: User`**

**`function main() {`**  
  **`program = registerUser("user@example.com", "secret123")`**  
    
  **`environment = {`**  
    **`database = PostgresDB.connect("localhost"),`**  
    **`email = SMTPEmail.connect("smtp.example.com")`**  
  **`}`**  
    
  **`result = run(program, environment)`**  
    
  **`match result {`**  
    **`Success(user) => println("User registered: " + user.email)`**  
    **`Failure(error) => println("Registration failed: " + error)`**  
  **`}`**  
**`}`**

(Description)

The effect system builds a description of what will happen (pure/lazy), but doesn't actually do anything until run executes it. run is called “unsafe” because it’s where effects actually happen. It’s the “edge of the world” where the pure functional program meets reality. Here, **Database.save()** writes to a database and **Email.send()** sends an email over the network. Both of these actions affect the world outside of the program, and are irreversible.

Note that the **environment** is cleanly separated from the rest of the program. This allows these external elements to be easily changed for both basic program configuration and for testing.

Here’s a more complex example that processes a collection of orders:

**`function processOrders(date) {`**  
  **`# Fetch orders using retry logic`**  
  **`orders = Database.query("SELECT * FROM orders WHERE date = ?", date)`**  
    **`.retry(maxAttempts = 3, backoff = exponential)`**  
    
  **`# Process orders in parallel`**  
  **`results = collectAllPar(orders, processOrder)`**  
    
  **`# Generate and cache report`**  
  **`reportData = generateReport(results)`**  
    
  **`cached = Cache.get("report:" + date)`**  
    **`.orElse {`**  
      **`path = FileSystem.write("reports/" + date + ".pdf", reportData)`**  
      **`Cache.set("report:" + date, path, ttl = 3600)`**  
      **`return path`**  
    **`}`**  
    
  **`return cached`**  
**`}`**

**`function processOrder(order) {`**  
  **`# Check inventory with timeout`**  
  **`inventory = Inventory.check(order.items)`**  
    **`.timeout(seconds = 5)`**  
    **`.orElse {`**  
      **`Logging.warn("Inventory check failed")`**  
      **`return estimateInventory(order.items)`**  
    **`}`**  
    
  **`# Calculate shipping if available`**  
  **`if !inventory {`**  
    **`return fail(OutOfStock(order.id))`**  
  **`}`**  
    
  **`shipping = HTTP.post(`**  
    **`"https://api.shipping.com/calculate",`**  
    **`body = order.shippingAddress`**  
  **`)`**  
    
  **`# Update order`**  
  **`Database.update(`**  
    **`"UPDATE orders SET shipping = ?, total = ? WHERE id = ?",`**  
    **`shipping.cost, order.subtotal + shipping.cost, order.id`**  
  **`)`**  
**`}`**

**`# Requires: Database, Inventory, HTTP, Cache, FileSystem, Logging`**  
**`# Errors: DBError | InventoryError | HTTPError | TimeoutError | OutOfStock`**  
**`# Returns: String (report path)`**

**`function main() {`**  
  **`program = processOrders("2024-01-15")`**  
    
  **`environment = {`**  
    **`database = PostgresDB.connect(config.dbUrl),`**  
    **`inventory = InventoryService.connect(config.inventoryUrl),`**  
    **`http = HTTPClient.create(timeout = 30),`**  
    **`cache = RedisCache.connect(config.redisUrl),`**  
    **`fileSystem = LocalFileSystem,`**  
    **`logging = ConsoleLogger`**  
  **`}`**  
    
  **`result = run(program, environment)`**  
    
  **`match result {`**  
    **`Success(reportPath) => println("Report saved to: " + reportPath)`**  
    **`Failure(error) => {`**  
      **`println("Processing failed: " + error)`**  
      **`exitCode = 1`**  
    **`}`**  
  **`}`**  
**`}`**

(Description)

The intermediate **results** value is initialized by calling **collectAllPar(orders, processOrder)**, which causes all the orders to be processed in parallel. We can do this because **processOrder** is an Effect and this makes it automatically safe to run in parallel.

In effect systems, **async** is typically implicit because all effects are potentially **async**. The sequential-looking code automatically handles async operations without requiring special syntax. The runtime manages it all.

Elements of the program that are most likely to change are distinctly isolated for easy modification and testing.

# Summary: Why Exceptions Failed

To integrate a component into your system, you must know, reliably, if and how that component will mess with your stuff. If you know this, you can write code to deal with it.

It might explode. For a long time, our strategies were:

1. Remain ignorant of the possibility  
2. Cross our fingers  
3. Accept it and restart the program  
4. If it’s really annoying, write some code to make it less bad

Exceptions were intended to prevent \#1. With exception *specifications*, a function advertises how it will explode. This only works if exceptions come with a type system that guarantees the exception specifications tell the truth, even if the function calls other functions that throw exceptions. Without fully enforcing exception specifications, they are basically useless other than producing slightly more valuable stack traces.

More importantly, exceptions are only one way that a component might mess with your stuff. To solve the problem we must reliably convey all the ways. This is the foundation of an Effect System: all composable components must guarantee that they’re correctly telling us all the ways they can mess with our stuff.

Once we have that, it produces many options: more automation when connecting components, the ability to decide at runtime if and when a component runs, automating async and parallel calls, and being able to easily produce all test cases.
